006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>pile</i> ‘stake, post’ (via Old English from Latin <i>pilum</i> ‘spike, javelin’), hence a topographic name for someone who lived near a stake or post serving as a landmark, or sometimes perhaps a nickname for a tall thin person.","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Pijl</b>: metonymic occupational name for a marksman or an arrowsmith, from <i>pijl</i> ‘arrow’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pile","meanings":["English (Devon and London): variant of   Pyle  .","French: from Old French <i>pile</i> ‘mortar, trough’ (from Latin <i>pila</i>), denoting a trough used for crushing or pounding various materials, such as lime, and in some cases the surname may have arisen as a metonymic occupational name for someone engaged in such work.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>pile</i> ‘pillar, column’ (from Latin <i>pila</i>), or a habitational name from any of the minor places in northern France named with this word."]},{"name":"Pyles","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Piles</b>, itself a variant of   Pyle   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Pyle was born in 1450, in Marlborough, Wiltshire, England, his father, John George Pyle, was 20 and his mother, Mary Anne Die Cromme, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Joane Pyle. He died in 1501, in Marlborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1450–1501":"1450–1501","1450–1471":"1450–1471","1470–1515":"1470–1515","1430–1450":"1430–1450","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1501":"1501","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","1515":"1515","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wiltshire,England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bapton, Wiltshire, England":"Bapton, Wiltshire, England","Marlborough, England":"Marlborough, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1450–1501":"1450–1501","1450–1471":"1450–1471","1470–1515":"1470–1515","1430–1450":"1430–1450","about 1470":"noin 1470","1501":"1501","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","1515":"1515","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wiltshire,England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bapton, Wiltshire, England":"Bapton, Wiltshire, England","Marlborough, England":"Marlborough, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1450–1501":"1450–1501","1450–1471":"1450–1471","1470–1515":"1470–1515","1430–1450":"1430–1450","a